I don't feel it's a matter of self respect.  When I was 14 the same thing happened to me.  It wasn't that I was worried about holding on to the relationship, I wasn't worried about what would happen if we broke up.  I can look back and say now that I was a little naive about it.  I recall sitting in the bathroom hours later and wondering if I would get pregnant.  What everyone should realize is that theae girls like myself are young.  I am 19 now and on my way to college im September.  One of the topics I have been studying is women, pregnancy, and abortion.  It's simply too harsh just to say there should be no reason for teenage pregnancy.  It happenes to the smartest, the poorest, the youngest, and the oldest.  <br>
There are reasons for everything.  Did anyone stop to think about how De'Yona was feeling?  How she felt about having a mother on drugs, with only her aging Grandmother to raise her?  How she felt about her neigborhood, and the things she saw there?  How she felt about her cousin, who had been there for her all of her life, and who had even taken her to her junior prom in the place of De'Yona's boyfriend, getting shot in the chest and dieing?  Her cousin who was the dominant male figure in her life, as her father wasn't really there.<br>
It's not really about having options, because I went to one of the best high schools in the country.  It's not about having self esteem, even though that does play a part.  It's about how each person deals with their pain, and how much support they receive to help them deal with it.  It's about expirience.  With teenage pregnancies, we just have to realize these girls are young, and no matter how much they hear they just don't know.  They're too young, too inexpirienced, to naive, to know!
